  "prompt": "What is the electric potential at the centre of sphere?",
  "response": "The electric potential at the center of a uniformly charged spherical shell is the same as the electric potential on its surface. For a uniformly charged solid sphere, the potential inside the sphere (including at the center) can be expressed in terms of the total charge and radius.\n\n1. **For a uniformly charged spherical shell:**\n   The electric potential \\( V \\) at any point inside a uniformly charged spherical shell, including the center, is given by:\n   \\[\n   V = \\frac{Q}{4\\pi \\epsilon_0 R}\n   \\]\n   where \\( Q \\) is the total charge on the shell, \\( R \\) is the radius of the shell, and \\( \\epsilon_0 \\) is the permittivity of free space.\n\n2. **For a uniformly charged solid sphere:**\n   The electric potential at a distance \\( r \\) from the center (where \\( r \\leq R \\)) is given by:\n   \\[\n   V = \\frac{Q}{4\\pi \\epsilon_0 R} + \\frac{Q}{8\\pi \\epsilon_0 R^3} \\cdot r^2\n   \\]\n   At the center of the sphere (where \\( r = 0 \\)):\n   \\[\n   V_{center} = \\frac{Q}{4\\pi \\epsilon_0 R}\n   \\]\n\nThus, in both cases, the electric potential at the center of a uniformly charged sphere (solid or shell) depends only on the total charge and the radius of the sphere. The center has the same potential as the surface of the shell and the maximum potential within the solid sphere.",
